                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7420a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Neville</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-22T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 22, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>179. Department’s 177, November 19, 5 p.m., second paragraph. Press despatches
                    from Tokyo report at considerable length in regard <pb facs="0547" n="435"
                        xml:id="pg_435"/> to recent developments affecting North China, Please
                    realize that, although press despatches are helpful, the Department in making
                    estimate of the situation must rely for information and comment in regard to
                    events and occurrences in Japan primarily on the Embassy. The Department would
                    appreciate receiving from you at your earliest practical convenience a telegram
                    setting forth such reliable information as you may be able to obtain in regard
                    to the North China situation, your analysis of that situation, and your estimate
                    of probable future developments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
